3) Why I chose "Control" and rejected "Stevie Nicks: Live in Chicago":
- As a CD enthusiast who enjoys listening to CDs broadly, I prioritize recordings that offer consistently high studio sound quality, clarity and strong production value that reward repeat listening on a home system. Studio pop/Adult Contemporary albums like "Control" are specifically engineered for that polished, radio-ready sonic presentation; they tend to contain multiple concise, catchy tracks with clear arrangements and production detail that make the CD format shine (dynamics, vocal layering, tight rhythm tracks).
- "Control" (Pop/Adult Contemporary) therefore better aligns with the general enjoyment of the CD listening experience: it's likely to deliver consistent sonic fidelity across tracks, memorable hooks that invite repeated plays, and production nuances that an attentive listener can appreciate on good playback equipment.
- I rejected "Stevie Nicks: Live in Chicago" not because it is inferior musically, but because its strengths are different and less aligned with the neutral preference I stated. Live Classic Rock/AOR recordings emphasize performance, crowd interaction and a live-room ambiance. Those attributes are great for capturing a concert experience, but they often include variable dynamics, stage talk, and a mix tailored to a live feel rather than the controlled clarity that many CD listeners prize for repeated, focused listening. If my priority is studio-polished, repeatable listening sessions that highlight production detail, a pop studio album better fits that goal than a live classic-rock set.
- In short: with no stated genre bias, I favored the album type that showcases what many CD enthusiasts most often seek from the format — precise studio production, strong track-to-track consistency and replay value — which points me to "Control" over a live Stevie Nicks recording whose virtues (concert realism, live energy) serve a different listening objective.

