 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences/dislikes (from my self-introduction): I strongly favor synth‑forward new wave/post‑punk albums with warm analog synth textures, preserved dynamics, spacious stereo imaging, polished mixes that reveal instrumental detail, concise danceable songs and cohesive single‑disc sequencing with consistent pacing. I also prefer meticulously engineered, album‑oriented releases made for start‑to‑finish CD listening and prize clear artistic identity, steady pacing, tight groove and immediacy in the rhythm section. I explicitly dislike greatest‑hits/compilation or remix‑led formats, radio‑trimmed singles, guest‑heavy reworkings, over‑sterilized mastering that flattens dynamics, and long ballad detours that break an album’s momentum.
Evaluation against the two candidates:
- Eurythmics – Greatest Hits: Sonically this release hits many of my core likes — it is synth‑forward/new‑wave, the remastering reportedly preserves bold ’80s analog synth textures and spacious stereo detail, and the package emphasizes tight start‑to‑finish sequencing and a reworked track flow that rewards repeat CD listening. That aligns with my desire for polished mixes that reveal detail, preserved dynamics, cohesive single‑disc sequencing, and a clear artistic identity (Annie Lennox’s authoritative lead supports that). Its principal conflict with my stated dislikes is that it is a “greatest hits” compilation — a format I generally avoid — but the specific notes about consistent mastering, preserved dynamics and purposeful sequencing mitigate the usual compilation drawbacks (radio trims, uneven mastering, stitched‑together pacing).
- Live in Chicago (raw, emotive set): This set scores well on preserved dynamics, instrumental detail and groove/ immediacy — all positives. However, it emphasizes audible audience ambience, room reverb, intimate live vocals and tasteful extended arrangements. Those live‑concert traits work against my preference for polished, album‑oriented studio listening: audience noise and extended arrangements can interrupt consistent pacing and the concise, danceable song structure I favor. The live set’s lack of studio polish and likely longer takes/arrangements make it less suited for focused CD‑style, start‑to‑finish listening as I prefer.
Decision rationale:
I choose Eurythmics – Greatest Hits because, despite the general dislike of compilation formats, this particular release aligns more closely with the strongest elements of my taste: synth‑forward new‑wave character, warm analog synth textures, preserved dynamics, spacious stereo imaging and purposefully curated sequencing that supports start‑to‑finish CD listening. The remaster’s emphasis on preserving analog texture and dynamics addresses my aversion to over‑sterilized mastering, and the reworked track flow and Annie Lennox’s consistent lead provide the clear artistic identity and steady pacing I prize. By contrast, the Live in Chicago set, while musically compelling, leans into concert immediacy (audience ambience, room reverb, extended arrangements) that undermines the concise, polished, album‑oriented listening experience I prefer and risks breaking the consistent pacing and tight, danceable song structure I value. For those reasons the Eurythmics release is the better match.

